369. Consulens juris et actor Causarum] Sees. i. 1. 9,11. AstoMessallaseeC.iii. 21. A. Cascellius was a jurisconsultus. The little that is known of him is given in the Dict. Biog. He must have been alive when this poem was written, but very old. The names are inverted. See C. ii. 2. 2, 11.

373. non concessere columnae] That is, the booksellers’ stalls. See S. i. 4. 71, 11.

375. Sardo cum melle] Sardinian and Corsican honeys appear to have been of inferior quality. See S. ii. 2. 15, 11. It appears poppy·seeds roasted and mixed with honey were served in early times at the second course. (Pliny xix. 8. 53.)

380. pilae discive trochive] See S. ii. 9, 11. ‘ Coronae’ are the crowds of spec- tators standing round to watch the games.

383. census equestrem Summam] ‘ Cen- sus ’ is a participle. His property was not less than 400,000 sesterces. See Epod. iv. 15, 11.; Epp. i. l. 57, n.
